{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "UV imaging may uncover structures and material phases in fossils that are difficult to detect using visible light, such as residual organics, growth lines and replacement calcites, with the latter known to fluoresce under ultraviolet light.",
    "While UV imaging is adept at identifying specific organic compounds, it poses a risk of altering or damaging samples (Chan et al. 2002).",
    "For DL applications, UV imaging provides additional data richness, particularly in cases with favorable surficial chemistry/mineralogy, where material phase contrast obtained by conventional optical imaging is lacking.",
    "It should be noted that ultraviolet imaging, which has little in the way of standardized sample preparation, and is often conducted using ad hoc lighting setups and consumer grade cameras (Crippa and Masini 2022), carries many of the issues related to image consistency encountered within optical microscopy, creating challenges in terms of its practical integration within DL model frameworks (Wen et al. 2014).",
    "Fluorescence Microscopy employs targeted excitation wavelengths to excite fluorescent molecules (fluorophores) within a sample, returning to a ground state via emitting light at a secondary emission wavelength, facilitating the focused observation of organic material in fossil studies (Stoneman et al. 2024; Lichtman and Conchello 2005; Kensche et al. 2013)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "While UV imaging is adept at identifying specific organic compounds, it poses a risk of altering or damaging samples (Chan et al. 2002).",
    "It should be noted that ultraviolet imaging, which has little in the way of standardized sample preparation, and is often conducted using ad hoc lighting setups and consumer grade cameras (Crippa and Masini 2022), carries many of the issues related to image consistency encountered within optical microscopy, creating challenges in terms of its practical integration within DL model frameworks (Wen et al. 2014).",
    "Fluorescence Microscopy employs targeted excitation wavelengths to excite fluorescent molecules (fluorophores) within a sample, returning to a ground state via emitting light at a secondary emission wavelength, facilitating the focused observation of organic material in fossil studies (Stoneman et al. 2024; Lichtman and Conchello 2005; Kensche et al. 2013)."
